Principal Components Analysis: Granatosky et al. 2014

Kelly Ostrofsky

April 6, 2015

Granatosky et al. 2014 - Lumbar vertebral morphology of flying, gliding, and suspensory mammals: Implications for the locomotor behavior of the subfossil lemurs Palaeopropithecus and Babakotia

Summary:

In this paper, the authors look at lumbar vertebral morphology to reconstruct locomotor behavior, in this case with respect to subfossil lemurs, Palaeopropithecus and Babakotia. They used seven measurements of the lumbar vertebrae that were chosen based on their functional significance, mostly with respect to their contribution to axial rigidity or mobility.

They describe locomotion such as inverted quadrupedalism, gliding, and flying as potentially requiring a more rigid spine. Previous studies found it difficult to distinguish these behaviors based on morphology, so this study used the lumbar vertebrae to try and make more fine-grained distinctions among different mammalian species, to better describe how the axial skeleton affects locomotor behavior in these extant mammals. This was then applied to two extinct species of sloth lemurs (Palaeopropithecus and Babakotia).

The previous reconstructions of Palaeopropithecus suggest it to be a more specialized inverted quadruped, like extant sloths. Babakotia is considered antipronograde, similar to living lorisids. Their hypotheses:

  1. There is a relationship between locomotor behavior and vertebral morphology
    • antipronograde, mitten-gliding, inverted quadrupeds, gliding, flying more axial RIGIDITY
    • pronograde, vertical clinging and leaping more axial MOBILITY
  2. Distinctions related to locomotor behavior can aid in the reconstruction of locomotor behavior of fossil species
    • sloth lemurs will occupy a similar morphospace to living inverted quadrupeds and/or antipronograde mammals

The linear measurements were divided by the geometric mean to account for effects of body size variation. They used PCA to explore variation in the metric data and examine the distribution of sample taxa in multidimensional morphospace. Linear variables were also log-transformed to normalize the distribution data for each species sample. The PCA was conducted using the correlation matrix in JMP. Now we will do it in R

PCA in R

There are several functions you can use to do PCA in R. Im going to go through one of them in detail, and then give examples of how to use the others (if you ever want to do a PCA, youll have plenty of code to look at).

PCA using prcomp() function in basic stats package

Help page for prcomp(): The calculation is done by a singular value decomposition of the (centered and possibly scaled) data matrix, not by using eigen on the covariance matrix. This is generally the preferred method for numerical accuracy.

vertpca1<- prcomp(data_log[,5:11], scale.=TRUE) 
#scale.= is whether or not the variables should be scaled to have unit variance before the analysis; default is scale.=F, but usually you would use T

Making the PCA plot

#The plot is grouped by locomotor category for the extant taxa, with the fossils as separate groups. So you need to put the fossil genus as locomotor category so it will be plotted correctly (when mapping shape or color to 'locomotor category' variable)
legendlabels<- factor(c("Babakotia", "Palaeopropithecus", "Antipronograde", "Flight", "Gliding", "Inverted quadrupedalism", "Mitten-gliding", "Pronograde", "Vertical clinging"))
legendlabels<- ordered(legendlabels, levels=legendlabels)

#The locomotor category variable is currently a factor, so I need to change it to the ordered factor I just made, so it will let me add in the fossil names
data_log$Locomotor_category <- ordered(data_log$Locomotor_category, levels=legendlabels)
data_log[38,3] <- "Palaeopropithecus"
data_log[39,3] <- "Babakotia"
PLOT PC1 vs.PC2
PLOTA_1x2 <- ggplot(data=PCscores1, 
       aes(x=PC1, y=PC2, shape=data_log$Locomotor_category)) + 
  geom_point(size=3) + theme_classic(15) + 
  labs(title="PCA of lumbar vertebral morphology \n(PC1x2)", 
       x=paste("Component 1 (",round(100*PC1.pve,2),"%)"), 
       y=paste("Component 2 (",round(100*PC2.pve,2),"%)")) + 
  theme(legend.title=element_blank(), legend.background=element_rect(color="black")) +
scale_shape_manual(labels=legendlabels,
                     values=c(3, 4, 22, 18, 17, 16, 1, 6, 15))

#FYI If you want 95% confidence ellipses instead of convex hulls using regular ggplot, you can use stat_ellipse(), which is p=0.95 default. It automatically creates ellipses by whatever you've grouped it by, or you can subset the dataframe like I've done for the convex hulls.
  • PC3 in their analysis explains 12.4% of the variation
    • PC3 separates mitten-gliders (blue circle), flying mammals (blue), and antipronograde mammals (purple) from the other taxa
    • Highest factor loading is the ML length of transverse processes
    • Babakotia has relatively short transverse processes, fits near antipronograde mammals; Palaeopropithecus has relatively ML elongated transverse processes

SUMMARY OF PAPER CONCLUSIONS, in case youre interested

  • Antipronograde, inverted quadrupeds, mitten-gliders, and flying mammals all have lumbar features associated with AXIAL RIGIDITY

  • Pronograde, vertical clinging species have features associated with more AXIAL MOBILITY

  • Contrary to predictions (but consistent with qualitative assessment of Boyer & Bloch 2008), gliding rodents and marsupials did not show features associated with stability, but rather MOBILITY

They do go into more detail into the ways each of the variables may contribute to more mobility or stability in the spine. They also have some interesting points in the discussion about mitten-gliders, a locomotor mode only observed in dermopterans (colugos). The results suggest that they are more similar to the inverted quadrupeds and antipronograde mammals rather than other gliders Granatosky et al. interpret this as further evidence for the hypothesis that axial rigidity is not necessarily a requirement for gliding behaviors (even though you see axial rigidity in the gliding mammals), but rather that axial rigidity is associated with what they do when they are not gliding. I.e., dermopterans (who group with the axial rigidity taxa), are inverted quadrupeds when not gliding; the gliders in this sample are all upright arboreal quadrupeds when not gliding. Thus axial rigidity in the dermopterans is likely for the suspensory locomotion rather than for gliding behavior (as argued by Boyer & Bloch 2008). They also discuss chiropterans (bats) and whether axial rigidity is associated with their inverted quadrupedal locomotion or flying, but they say that this question remains difficult to untangle.

Other main results, re: subfossil lemurs, are largely consistent with previous studies:

  • living sloths are the closest analog for Palaeopropithecus (obligate inverted quadrupeds)

  • while highly suspensory, Babakotia may have been capable of a more generalized locomotor repertoire similar to living lorisids, or (as proposed by others) Pongo

Now we can just go through the other examples of how to run a PCA and different ways to plot results.

Plotting with ggbiplot()

This is another way to make a biplot for principal components using ggplot2.

library(devtools)
install_github("ggbiplot", "vqv")

PCA using princomp() function; you can set it to cor=FALSE to use the covariance matrix.

Help page for princomp(): The calculation is done using eigen on the correlation or covariance matrix, as determined by cor. This is done for compatibility with the S-PLUS result. A preferred method of calculation is to use svd on x, as is done in prcomp.

vertpca2 <- princomp(data_log[,5:11], cor=T)
vertpca2

PCscores2 <- as.data.frame(vertpca2$scores)#save PC scores
PC1_2<- PCscores2[,1]
PC2_2 <- PCscores2[,2]
PC3_2<- PCscores2[,3]

#For this one you can't directly access the PVE, but you can calculate it (you can check it is the same by going back to the summary above)
vertpca2.propvar<- vertpca2.results$sdev^2/sum(vertpca2.results$sdev^2)
PC1_2.pve <- vertpca2.propvar[[1]]
PC2_2.pve <- vertpca2.propvar[[2]]
PC3_3.pve <- vertpca2.propvar[[3]]

Making the PCA plot

This is the same as before - you just saved the PC scores, etc. differently. Note that the results are almost the exact same as using prcomp() above.

#Same thing as before, plotting using ggplot: PC1xPC2
PLOTB_1x2<- ggplot(data=PCscores2, aes(x=PC1_2, y=PC2_2, color=data_log$Locomotor_category, shape=data_log$Locomotor_category)) + 
  geom_point(size=3) + theme_classic(15) + 
  labs(title="PCA of lumbar vertebral morphology \n(PC1x2)", 
       x=paste("PC1 (",round(100*PC1_2.pve,2),"%)"), 
       y=paste("PC2 (",round(100*PC2_2.pve,2),"%)")) + 
  theme(legend.title=element_blank(), legend.background=element_rect(color="black")) +
  scale_shape_manual(labels=legendlabels,
                     values=c(3, 4, 22, 18, 17, 16, 1, 6, 15)) + 
    scale_color_manual(labels=legendlabels,
                     values=c("black", "black", "purple", "blue", "orange", 
                              "springgreen4", "steelblue4", "red", "deeppink"))

PCA using PCA() function from FactoMineR package

library(FactoMineR)
#includes plot.PCA() function, but it just plots the individuals factor map

vertpca3 <- PCA(data_log[,5:11])

#note that it automatically produces an individuals factor map (PC1x2 for individuals) and a variables factor map - this is a nice way to visualize how the variables are loaded along the PCs

#also note that in this one, I think the factor loadings were given opposite signs (+/-) so the projection of the variables is in the opposite direction of the previous one

#use argument axes=c(1,2) or c(1,3) etc. to specify which components you want to be plotted. e.g., to see PC1x3:
PCA(data_log[,5:11], axes=c(1,3))
